<DOC><DOCNO> AP890414-0297 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1843EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-GMProxy 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0361</FIRST><SECOND>AM-GM Proxy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0370</SECOND><HEAD>GM Releases Its Proxy Statement; Smith Gets $3.6 Million Last Year</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-7 with 2 grafs of UAW comment.</HEAD><BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   General Motors Corp. Chairman Roger Smithreceived about $3.6 million in salary and benefits last year,placing last in terms of compensation among the chiefs of thenation's Big Three automakers, GM said Friday.   In its annual proxy statement, the nation's largest automakersaid Smith received $983,000 in salary, exercised $1 million instock options and had $68,833 contributed by the company to asavings and stock purchase plan.   Smith also received $1.5 million worth of stock which could beheld or liquidated during the following three years.   The proxy statement said that in addition, Smith was paid $1million early this year for the company's performance during thefive previous years.   United Auto Workers President Owen Bieber and Vice PresidentDonald Ephlin, head of the union's GM Department, issued a jointstatement Friday afternoon criticizing the company's executivecompensation amounts.   They said it was ``irresponsible for the ship's officers to beseen feasting in the officer's mess when down below the waves arepounding and the ship is taking on water.''   Earlier this week, the nation's second-largest automaker, FordMotor Co., said its chairman, Donald Petersen, received $10.5million in 1988 compensation, most of it coming in stock options.   No. 3 Chrysler Corp. said its chairman, Lee Iacocca, was awarded$3.7 million and future stock options from the nation's No. 3automaker.   The GM proxy statement also listed 1988 salaries, exercisedstock options and company stock and savings plan contributions forfour other officers: Executive Vice President F. Alan Smith,$764,796; President Robert Stempel, $688,594; Vice Chairman DonaldAtwood, who is being considered to become deputy defense secretary,$668,750; and Executive Vice President Lloyd Reuss, $535,000.   The statement also contained a number of proposals presented byshareholders to be voted on during the GM annual meeting May 19 inDetroit, including three proposals for GM to cut its economic tiesto South Africa. The company's board of directors is recommendingvotes against all three.</TEXT></DOC>